<body>
          
<div type="edition" xml:lang="tam-Latn" rendition="class:tamil maturity:83215">
                          
	<p>
		<lb n="1"/><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/> <unclear>t</unclear>ārayar maṭam-uṭaiyāṉ</p>
	
</div>
          
<div type="apparatus">
	<listApp>
		
		<app loc="1">
			<lem><gap reason="illegible" quantity="1" unit="character"/> <unclear>t</unclear>ārayar</lem>
			<rdg source="bib:Ramachandran1992_01">tārayar</rdg>
		</app>
		
	</listApp>
</div>
  
<div type="translation" source="bib:Ramachandran1992_01">
  	
  	<p n="1">The Lord <supplied reason="explanation">Buddha</supplied> of the <foreign>maṭha</foreign> of the Tārayar <supplied reason="explanation">i.e., Theriyas or Sthaviras or the Elders</supplied></p>			
				
</div>
<div type="translation" resp="part:emfr">
 	
 	<p n="1">The Lord <supplied reason="subaudible">of</supplied> the <foreign>matḥa</foreign> of <gap reason="ellipsis"/>.</p>
 	
 </div>
      	
<div type="commentary">
	
	<p><bibl><ptr target="bib:Ramachandran1992_01"/></bibl> comments thus: <quote><!--converted to DHARMA transliteration conventions-->It is not clear if this inscription refers to the image itself in which case it would serve as its label meaning the "Lord," i.e., Buddha, of, i.e., worshipped in, the <foreign>maṭha</foreign> or monastery of the Theras, the Elders. Or the "Lord of the <foreign>maṭha</foreign>" may merely mean the head of the <foreign>maṭha</foreign> of Theras, any spiritual head or guide. The Buddha was more probably meant (cf. inscription 43<!--add DHARMA corpus cross-ref-->).</quote></p>
	
</div>
		      	
